This paper focuses on the performance of data ingestion and checkpointing in TensorFlow, a DL framework. Therefore, it is likely to belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. Additionally, the paper measures the I/O performance of TensorFlow, which is a key aspect of DL applications, making it likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-categories. The paper also uses a mini-application based on AlexNet, which is a popular DL model for image classification, indicating that it could belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the use of a burst buffer, which is a technique commonly used in scientific computing, suggesting that it could belong to the Scientific Computing (cs.SC) sub-category.
